### [Reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)

Learning through interaction and consequence. The agent against the world.

*   **[Q-learning](/Q-learning):** An off-policy temporal difference learning algorithm used in [reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning) to find the optimal action-selection policy for a given finite Markov decision process. It learns the value of taking an action in a state.
*   **[Policy gradient](/Policy_gradient_method):** A class of [reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning) algorithms that directly learn a policy, which is a probability distribution over actions given states. It learns *what* to do.
*   **[SARSA](/State%E2%80%93action%E2%80%93reward%E2%80%93state%E2%80%93action):** An on-policy temporal difference learning algorithm used in [reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning). It learns the value of taking an action in a state and then following a given policy.
*   **[Temporal difference (TD)](/Temporal_difference_learning):** A class of model-free prediction and control algorithms in [reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning) that learn from experience by bootstrapping. It learns from estimates of future values.
*   **[Multi-agent](/Multi-agent_reinforcement_learning):** [Reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning) problems where multiple agents interact within a shared environment. The complexity multiplies.
*   **[Self-play](/Self-play_(reinforcement_learning_technique)):** A technique in [reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning) where an agent learns by playing against itself, generating its own training data. It's a solitary, recursive form of learning.

